There’s actually a name for this phenomenon, and there are several related concepts depending on what you want to emphasize.

* Independent discovery – Two or more people arrive at the same idea without influencing each other. This is the standard term in science and mathematics.
* Multiple discovery or simultaneous invention – Common when many people independently develop the same invention or theory around the same time.
* Convergent evolution (used metaphorically) – Different paths leading to the same solution because the “environment” of ideas favors it.
* Reinventing the wheel – Usually implies rediscovering something already known, though with a negative connotation.
* Personal discovery – Not a formal term, but a useful way to describe learning or creating something genuinely new to you, regardless of whether others already know it.

For creativity, there’s an important distinction:

* Objective novelty: New to humanity.
* Subjective novelty: New to the individual.

Psychologists often recognize subjective novelty as real creativity because your mind generated the idea independently rather than recalling it.

For Pantheon, this is actually an interesting pattern. You could think of it as:

First-person novelty — an idea is original within the explorer’s own search path, even if it already exists globally.

Or more poetically:

The map was old. The journey was new.

That captures something important: rediscovering an idea yourself often gives you a much deeper understanding than simply being told it. The value isn’t only in whether the destination is globally novel—it’s in the path your own mind took to get there. That path becomes part of your reasoning toolkit.